<p>With Georgia Power's rate of 12.3¬¢/kWh, a typical 2,000 square foot Atlanta home can spend \$1,800-2,400 annually on HVAC energy costs. Upgrading from a 13 SEER system to an 18 SEER unit can reduce cooling costs by 25-30%, translating to \$400-600 in annual savings. Proper system sizing is critical in Atlanta's humid climate, as oversized units short-cycle and fail to adequately remove humidity. Variable-speed air handlers and two-stage compressors provide superior humidity control while reducing energy consumption during partial load conditions, which occur frequently in Atlanta's variable weather patterns.</p>

<h2>Maintenance Requirements</h2>

<p>Atlanta's hot-humid climate accelerates wear on HVAC components, making regular maintenance essential for optimal performance and longevity. Systems should receive professional tune-ups twice yearly - spring preparation for cooling season and fall winterization. Monthly filter changes are crucial during peak usage periods, as Atlanta's pollen levels and humidity can quickly clog filters and reduce system efficiency. Outdoor units require regular cleaning to remove debris, pollen, and organic growth that can impair heat transfer. Professional duct cleaning every 3-5 years helps maintain indoor air quality and system efficiency in Atlanta's humid environment.</p>

